<html><head><meta name="color-scheme" content="light dark"><meta charset="utf-8"></head><body><pre>{"id":1560,"date":"2024-07-31T23:55:00","date_gmt":"2024-07-31T13:55:00","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/melbacg.au\/?p=1560"},"modified":"2024-08-16T12:36:26","modified_gmt":"2024-08-16T02:36:26","slug":"organisational-dualism","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/melbacg.au\/organisational-dualism\/","title":{"rendered":"Anarchism 101: Organisational Dualism"},"content":{"rendered":"\n&lt;p&gt;The Melbourne Anarchist Communist Group follows the approach known as \u2018organisational dualism\u2019 \u2013 a strategy which dates back to the beginning of the anarchist movement. We argue that anarchists need to be organised at two levels: the \u2018political\u2019 level and the \u2018mass\u2019 level.&lt;\/p&gt;\n\n\n\n&lt;p&gt;Politically, we organise among ourselves as anarchists. We advocate formal organisations which operate on the basis of theoretical unity, a shared strategy, and collective responsibility. The basis for organisation at the political level is ideological. The political organisation unites convinced revolutionaries and multiplies our efforts to intervene as an anarchist minority within the broader working class movement.&lt;\/p&gt;\n\n\n\n&lt;p&gt;At the same time, we organise alongside our fellow workers wherever we can unite as a class in direct struggle against exploitation and oppression. Despite their bureaucratisation, the largest and most important mass organisations of this kind are the trade unions. The basis for organisation at the mass level is not ideological, but a willingness to fight together as workers \u2013 as a class.&lt;\/p&gt;\n\n\n\n&lt;p&gt;We see the distinction between political and mass organisations as vital. An anarchist political organisation requires a high level of political agreement, so that we can maintain a clear analysis and strategy while adapting to new developments in the class struggle. Meanwhile, mass organisations should unite as many workers as possible. Political organisations can\u2019t be so broad that they become incoherent, and mass organisations like unions shouldn\u2019t impose a strict political test before workers can join.&lt;\/p&gt;\n\n\n&lt;div class=\"wp-block-image\"&gt;\n&lt;figure class=\"aligncenter size-medium\"&gt;&lt;img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"247\" height=\"300\" src=\"https:\/\/melbacg.au\/wp-content\/uploads\/2024\/07\/clip-from-spanish-civil-war-poster-workers-walking-247x300.jpg\" alt=\"Two workers walking together, one with a book and one in work wear. \" class=\"wp-image-1563\" srcset=\"https:\/\/melbacg.au\/wp-content\/uploads\/2024\/07\/clip-from-spanish-civil-war-poster-workers-walking-247x300.jpg 247w, https:\/\/melbacg.au\/wp-content\/uploads\/2024\/07\/clip-from-spanish-civil-war-poster-workers-walking.jpg 490w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 247px) 100vw, 247px\" \/&gt;&lt;figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\"&gt;Image by Cantos&lt;\/figcaption&gt;&lt;\/figure&gt;\n&lt;\/div&gt;\n\n\n&lt;p&gt;We reject the strategy of separating ourselves from the mass of workers by forming explicitly ideological unions. We do want anarchist methods of organisation and struggle to be adopted within unions and other campaigns. An \u2018anarchist union\u2019, however, would either isolate itself from the majority who don\u2019t already share our ideas or instantly dilute its \u2018anarchism\u2019 by making the majority of its members non-anarchist workers.&lt;\/p&gt;\n\n\n\n&lt;p&gt;By grouping together all workers on the basis of class, we avoid the problem of separating more radical workers from less radical ones, and maintain the potential for those workers to be influenced in meetings and in our organising.&lt;\/p&gt;\n\n\n\n&lt;p&gt;Organisational dualism differs from the approach of most Marxist groups in two key ways. First, anarchist political organisations are federalist and controlled from the bottom up.&lt;\/p&gt;\n\n\n\n&lt;p&gt;Second, we reject substituting our organisations for the working class movement. Anarchist organisations don\u2019t aim to \u2018lead\u2019 struggles in the sense of taking them over or giving orders from above. Instead, we fight for the leadership of our ideas and methods. Members of an anarchist political organisation are the most active and militant members of the union in their workplace and organise workplaces which are unorganised. We fight against top-down, bureaucratic organisation in both our unions and social movements and encourage direct action under the control of the rank and file. In doing so, we demonstrate the validity of our ideas and build toward the kind of self-organised working class power which will be necessary to overthrow capitalism.&lt;\/p&gt;\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"The Melbourne Anarchist Communist Group follows the approach known as \u2018organisational dualism\u2019 \u2013 a strategy which dates back to the beginning of the anarchist movement. We argue that anarchists need to be organised at two levels: the \u2018political\u2019 level and the \u2018mass\u2019 level.\n&lt;a class=\"moretag\" href=\"https:\/\/melbacg.au\/organisational-dualism\/\"&gt; [...]&lt;\/a&gt;","protected":false},"author":1,"featured_media":1567,"comment_status":"closed","ping_status":"","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":{"_coblocks_attr":"","_coblocks_dimensions":"","_coblocks_responsive_height":"","_coblocks_accordion_ie_support":"","footnotes":""},"categories":[29,2],"tags":[61],"class_list":["post-1560","post","type-post","status-publish","format-standard","has-post-thumbnail","hentry","category-anarchism","category-anvil","tag-theory"],"_links":{"self":[{"href":"https:\/\/melbacg.au\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/1560","targetHints":{"allow":["GET"]}}],"collection":[{"href":"https:\/\/melbacg.au\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts"}],"about":[{"href":"https:\/\/melbacg.au\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/types\/post"}],"author":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/melbacg.au\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/users\/1"}],"replies":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/melbacg.au\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/comments?post=1560"}],"version-history":[{"count":4,"href":"https:\/\/melbacg.au\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/1560\/revisions"}],"predecessor-version":[{"id":1578,"href":"https:\/\/melbacg.au\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/1560\/revisions\/1578"}],"wp:featuredmedia":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/melbacg.au\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/media\/1567"}],"wp:attachment":[{"href":"https:\/\/melbacg.au\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/media?parent=1560"}],"wp:term":[{"taxonomy":"category","embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/melbacg.au\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/categories?post=1560"},{"taxonomy":"post_tag","embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/melbacg.au\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/tags?post=1560"}],"curies":[{"name":"wp","href":"https:\/\/api.w.org\/{rel}","templated":true}]}}</pre><div class="json-formatter-container"></div></body></html>